Juliet Pierpont's descent from Rev. Thomas Hooker. 7th-generation Hooker descendant.","marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00361","marriage_number":1,"children_ids":[]},{"spouse_id":"X00360","children_ids":["HD1171","HD1172","HD1173","HD1174"],"marriage_number":2,"date_year":1865,"date_month":5,"date_day":31}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":2,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["business"],"notable_blurb":"America's most powerful private banker","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._P._Morgan","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"cross_connections":[{"type":"civic_connection","related_id":"X00744","display_label":"Roosevelt dissolved his Northern Securities Trust 1904","link_text":"Theodore Roosevelt"},{"type":"professional","related_id":"I01429","link_text":"Thomas Hastings","display_label":"produced building designs for him as Gilded Age architect"},{"type":"parallel_careers","related_id":"I01635","display_label":"amassed a Gilded Age art collection rivaling Morgan's"}],"bio":{"display_name":"John Pierpont Morgan","first_name":"John","last_name":"Morgan","middle_name":"Pierpont","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST087","relationship":"founder","years":"1906","institution_blurb":"Built his private library on East 36th Street to house his collection of medieval manuscripts, Old Master drawings, and rare books; opened to the public after his death."}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"business","header":"Personally bailed out the US Treasury — twice","body":"During the 1895 gold crisis he led a syndicate that supplied the federal government with $65 million in gold to prevent default. During the Panic of 1907 he locked the heads of New York's banks in his library until they pledged the funds to halt a wave of failures."},{"number":2,"category":"business","header":"Created the first billion-dollar corporation","body":"In 1901 he merged Carnegie Steel with smaller producers to form U.S. Steel, capitalized at $1.4 billion when the entire federal budget was under $500 million. Andrew Carnegie reportedly named his price on a slip of paper, and Morgan replied 'I accept' without negotiation."},{"number":3,"category":"character","header":"Disfiguring rhinophyma made him hate cameras","body":"A skin condition called rhinophyma transformed his nose into a bulbous purple mass in middle age. He refused most photographs and detested social engagements; the few portraits that exist were heavily retouched on his orders."},{"number":4,"category":"legacy","header":"Built one of the world's greatest art collections","body":"He spent decades and a fortune assembling Renaissance manuscripts, Old Masters paintings, and ancient artifacts; at his death in 1913 his collection was valued near $50 million. Half of it was donated to the Metropolitan Museum of Art by his son and remains core to the Met today."},{"number":5,"category":"death","header":"Pujo Committee testimony broke his health","body":"In December 1912 he was forced to testify before the Pujo Committee investigating his 'money trust'; the Senate hearings exhausted him and he sailed for Europe to recover. He died in Rome on March 31, 1913, three months after taking the stand."}],"slug":"john-morgan-1837"},"HD1217":{"id":"HD1217","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":8,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"X00359","mother_id":"HD1166"},"tags":[],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1839},"death":{"year":1896},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00386","children_ids":["HD1238","HD1239"],"marriage_number":1}],"gender":"female","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Sarah Spencer Morgan","first_name":"Sarah","middle_name":"Spencer","maiden_name":"Morgan","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"sarah-morgan-1839"},"HD1218":{"id":"HD1218","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"generation_from_thomas":8,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"X00359","mother_id":"HD1166"},"tags":["died_young"],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1846,"month":4,"day":6,"city":"Hartford","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1858,"month":3,"day":12,"city":"London","state":"England"},"gender":"male","marriages":[],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[{"type":"naming_pattern","related_id":"HD1238","display_label":"Namesake nephew born 1867 nine years after his death","notes":"HD1218 (1846-1858) was the eldest son of Junius Spencer Morgan I + Juliet Pierpont. His maternal nephew HD1238 (1867-1932) was born nine years after HD1218's death at age 11, given the same first/middle name and the same 'II' suffix — the namesake-after-early-death family pattern. Uncle/nephew relationship — outside §5 spouse/parent/child/sibling exclusion list."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Junius Spencer Morgan II (the elder)","first_name":"Junius","last_name":"Morgan","suffix":"II","middle_name":"Spencer","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"death","header":"Died in London at age eleven, 1858","body":"Junius Spencer Morgan II 'the elder' died March 12, 1858 in London England at age eleven, having been born in Hartford Connecticut on April 6, 1846. The boy was the eldest son and namesake of his father Junius Spencer Morgan I, who was building the London-based banking firm that would later evolve into J.P. Morgan and Company. Cause of death is not documented in available sources."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Namesake nephew later re-used the II suffix","body":"Nine years after this Junius II's 1858 death, his maternal nephew was born in 1867 and given the same name with the same 'II' suffix — Junius Spencer Morgan II 'the younger' (1867-1932), the Princeton librarian and art collector. The namesake-after-early-death family pattern was common in nineteenth-century New England elite families when a child died young before establishing the suffix-numbering further. The 'II' suffix was effectively reset for the next-generation namesake."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Younger brother of financier J.P. Morgan Sr.","body":"Junius II 'the elder' was the second son of Junius Spencer Morgan I and Juliet Pierpont, born nine years after his older brother J. Pierpont Morgan Sr. His full siblings included Sarah Spencer Morgan, mother of his namesake nephew. His death at eleven left J. Pierpont Morgan Sr. as the eldest surviving son to inherit the family banking enterprise that would become J.P. Morgan and Company."}],"slug":"junius-morgan-ii-1846"},"HD1219":{"id":"HD1219","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":8,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"X00359","mother_id":"HD1166"},"tags":[],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1847},"death":{"year":1923},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00985","children_ids":["HD2752","HD2753"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1871,"date_month":7,"da