ous musician with a bad reputation","body":"Pierpont twice walked out on his wife and children, once for the California Gold Rush and once for Savannah. He was the restless black sheep of an otherwise upright New England family.","number":2},{"category":"military","header":"He fought for the South he had joined","body":"In sharp contrast to his fiercely abolitionist family, Pierpont served the Confederacy and wrote Confederate war songs such as Strike for the South. The composer of America's merriest carol spent the war on the slaveholding side.","number":3},{"category":"family","header":"His father and nephew were famous men","body":"Pierpont's father was the abolitionist minister and poet John Pierpont, and his nephew was the financier J. P. Morgan. His daughter Lillie became one of the first women to serve as a federal Indian agent in Florida.","number":4}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"parallel_careers","related_id":"HD6102","display_label":"a descendant who composed and taught piano"}],"bio":{"display_name":"James Lord Pierpont","first_name":"James","last_name":"Pierpont","middle_name":"Lord","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1780775642/James_Lord_Pierpont_vjxfzb.jpg"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"james-pierpont-1822"},"X00363":{"id":"X00363","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"tags":[],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1822},"death":{"year":1856},"gender":"female","number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"HD1168","date_year":1846,"children_ids":["HD1176","HD1192"]}],"parents":{},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_categ